						Magnes in pectore: Adamas in ore: }
						in manu, Pyropus.
					</marginalia_text>
				</position>
			</language>
			<translation>
				A magnet in the breast, adamant in the mouth, bronze in the hand.
			</translation>
		</marginalia>
		
		<marginalia hand="Italian">
			<language ident="LA">
				<position place="right_margin" book_orientation="0">
					<marginalia_text>
						Quicquid
					</marginalia_text>
				</position>
				<position place="intext" book_orientation="0">
					<marginalia_text>
						geritur negotij,
					</marginalia_text>
				</position>
				<position place="right_margin" book_orientation="0">
					<marginalia_text>
						Eutrapel[u]s
					</marginalia_text>
					<person name="Eutrapelus"/>
				</position>
				<position place="intext" book_orientation="0">
					<marginalia_text>
						tribus Mnemosynis omnes actores excellit:
					</marginalia_text>
					<person name="Mnemosyne"/>
				</position>
				<position place="right_margin" book_orientation="0">
					<marginalia_text>
						Vigore, ratione, et diligentia.
						Qua[e] facil&egrave; omnes defectus =
						
						) = supplent; et generale
					</marginalia_text>
					<emphasis method="pen" type="straight" text="Vigore, ratione, et diligentia"/>
				</position>
				<position place="intext" book_orientation="0">
					<marginalia_text>
						( habent imperiu[m] in [omnes deleted] quasuis speciales functiones.
					</marginalia_text>
				</position>
			</language>
			<translation>
				Whatever affair is being managed, Eutrapelus surpasses all actors of the tribe of Mnemosyn <!-- CG: Perhaps the 'cult of memory'? --> <!--JG: I'd leave the literal translation here-->
				with vigor, reason, and diligence. These easily make up for all defects and hold a common empire over any
				particular executions whatsoever.
			</translation>
		</marginalia>
		
		<marginalia hand="Italian">
			<language ident="LA">
				<position place="intext" book_orientation="0">
					<marginalia_text>
						Fortitudine superatur Inuidia:
						Emblema Leonis conculcantis Draconem.
					</marginalia_text>
				</position>
			</language>
			<translation>
				Envy is defeated by strength:
				the emblem of the lion trampling the dragon.
			</translation>
		</marginalia>
		<marginalia hand="Italian">
			<language ident="LA">
				<position place="intext" book_orientation="0">
					<marginalia_text>
						Qui incipit frigescere; aut desinit excellere: incipit
					</marginalia_text>
				</position>
				<position place="right_margin" book_orientation="0">
					<marginalia_text>
						sordescere
					</marginalia_text>
				</position>
				<position place="intext" book_orientation="0">
					<marginalia_text>
						in Seipso;
						apppud alios vilescere.
					</marginalia_text>
				</position>
			</language>
			<translation>
				Whoever begins to grow cold, or whoever ceases to excel, begins to grow mean and become vile with other people.
					<!-- CG: This marginalia and the following are challenging to distinguish. I feel like this is the way that makes the most sense. --> <!--JG: I agree. You might want to translate 'in seipso', though-->				
			</translation>
		</marginalia>
		<marginalia hand="Italian">
			<language ident="LA">
				<position place="intext" book_orientation="0">
					<marginalia_text>
						( Animus est, qui efficit Excellentes: vt etiam Beatos.)
					</marginalia_text>
				</position>
			</language>
			<translation>
				The rational soul is that which produces excellent man, and even blessed ones.
			</translation>
		</marginalia>
		
		<marginalia hand="Italian">
			<language ident="LA">
				<position place="tail" book_orientation="0">
					<marginalia_text>
						Nunq[uam] remittenda Summi Boni intentio.
					</marginalia_text>
				</position>
			</language>
			<translation>
				Attention toward the highest good must never be slackened.
			</translation>
		</marginalia>
		
		<marginalia hand="Italian">
			<language ident="LA">
				<position place="left_margin" book_orientation="90">
					<marginalia_text>
						Nunq[uam] languescit Eutrapeli affectatio: nunq[uam] deflorescit dignitas. 
					</marginalia_text>
					<person name="Eutrapelus"/>
				</position>
			</language>
			<translation>
				The striving of Eutrapelus never languishes; his dignity never fades.
			</translation>
		</marginalia>
		
		<marginalia hand="Italian">
			<language ident="LA">
				<position place="right_margin" book_orientation="270">
					<marginalia_text>
						Alij solliciti de honore; hic de dignitate.
						Meritis expendite Causam.
					</marginalia_text>
				</position>
			</language>
			<translation>
				Others are concerned with honor; this man is concerned with dignity.
				Decide the cause by merits.
			</translation>
		</marginalia>
		
